    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "df5423490fe9a3d3b6cfabd003e3cc29",
      "text": "Stallman mentions the dangers some [[e-books]] bring compared to paper books, with the example of the [[Amazon Kindle]] [[e-reader]] that prevents the copying of e-books and allows Amazon to order automatic deletion of a book. He says that such e-books present a big step backward with respect to paper books by being less easy to use, copy, lend to others or sell, also mentioning that Amazon e-books cannot be bought anonymously. His short story \"[[The Right to Read]]\" provides a picture of a dystopian future if the right to share books is impeded. He objects to many of the terms within typical [[end-user license agreement]]s that accompany e-books."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5ca678d8331dd661b0e8c23d9897f199",
      "text": "Stallman discourages the use of several storage technologies such as DVD or Blu-ray ([[Blu-ray Disc]]) video discs because the content of such media is encrypted. He considers manufacturers' use of encryption on non-secret data (to force the user to view certain promotional material ([[User operation prohibition]])) as a conspiracy."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "62f656144736d9060116192bba814216",
      "text": "Stallman has suggested that the United States government may encourage the use of [[software as a service]] because this would allow them to access users' data without needing a [[search warrant]]."
    },
